No one is talking about sex enough. Parents to their kids, friends to friends and definitely not partner to partner. There's a dark cloud of mysterious perversion & shame looming over sex in our culture, and it's ridiculous, really. It draws kids in too early and without proper education because parents feel "awkward" talking about it. (Perhaps if adults discussed it with their partners, they'd feel less awkward with their children?) Friends have questions and concerns they'd love to address with their peers, but they worry it is "TMI." And women and men go through life unfulfilled, unsatisfied, but have they talked about it with their partners? Probably not. -
Part of my mission as a boudoir photographer is to get sex talked about. I want to get you ladies talking to the people you trust about positions & orgasms, weird stuff you're apprehensive to enjoy, what isn't working, what definitely IS working. The sad stuff, the funny stuff. All of it. Because if we don't talk about it, it can't get better. And you deserve to feel incredible. -

I've photographed these flags at this church the last three times I've been to New York City. The first time, the banner stated that each flag represents a fallen soldier. The second time each one was for a victim of violence in the city. This time, all the banner said was "Peace Flags. Tie a Ribbon for Peace." My heart sank. There is so much hate in the world that specificity would be trite. It almost seemed a desperate plea. Just, peace. All we want is peace. -
Sad and scared and angry, I asked Ricky last night, "how do we see the good?" He told me, "be it. Look at us. Look at your family. Look at the babies you care for. We're the good. We will win." -
Being the good is getting harder and harder, but we don't have a choice. The lovers have to be loud. The light has to be bright. Get angry. Shout out loud. Love hard today. Cry if you need to. Appreciate today. Teach someone something new. Reach out. Connect. We're all we've got. -

This week was hard. Life threw a lot at all of us, and it just kept coming. 
I don't always handle fear & stress very well. Thanks to good family, friends and a therapist or two, I've learned the tools to redirect my negative thoughts, and for years now I'm generally doing just fine on the anxiety front. 
Not so much this week. I had an anxiety, almost panic, attack that rocked my brain off its balance beam, and probably scared the shit out of my amazing boyfriend. Everything is fine, and it will be fine, but I didn't know that at the time, and I couldn't be convinced. 
Once I was able to exit the compulsive, cyclical thoughts, I realized I'd never shared this part of me online. Which is fine. Privacy is good. But the reason I wasn't sharing it was because I was trying to maintain this "boss lady" image, and a woman who struggles with anxiety didn't fit that persona in my mind. 
Excuse my language, but fuck. that. Struggling with anxiety AND being a lady boss makes me so much of a fucking badass I can't even stand it. 
There are days I can't find reasons to turn off Netflix & get off the couch, but I do it and run my business. Sometimes I'm crushed by worrying about what people think of me, but then I push those thoughts down and put myself and my art out there anyway. My fear of the awful things that happen in this world paralyzes me, but I take a deep breath and I keep fucking living as hard as I can. 
And I know I'm not alone. To those of you rocking the socks off your life despite mental illness, IN SPITE of mental illness, I love you & wish I could hug you. You're a badass, and we need you in this world.

I started doing boudoir photography because I wanted to make people feel beautiful. Whoops.

It didn't take very many clients for me to learn that I can't do that. 
I can't make you feel okay about your thighs or your nose. I can't make you feel okay that you aren't the size you want to be. I can't make you feel okay that your boobs look different after breastfeeding.

I've had as many reasons as I've had women in front of my camera. But if your reason to do a boudoir shoot is to feel beautiful, let's take a look on the inside before we look at the outside. 
You're Incredible.

Oh, The Places You'll Go // I hadn't read it for years, and I even resisted rereading it due to its commencement-related popularity. So when the three year old I watch chose it at the library, I had a twinge of dread strike me. We took it home and got cozy together on the porch swing. The breeze was so strong I barely had to push us. I started reading this ominous book, and by page three I was in my most animated reading to a child voice, effortlessly leaping from word to word. He giggled as I read, and when the book was over I realized something I think I knew all along, but was reluctant to admit. I was scared to read Oh, The Places You'll Go. All these years I was afraid to open the pages that everyone guaranteed could inspire even the darkest souls. I was afraid because there was a time I had everything going for me, but I didn't see it, and I took several wrong turns. For a long time, I thought these wrong turns were preventing me from climbing my mountains and experiencing an extraordinary life. Eventually, though, I realized that it is not my past mistakes that define me. It's what I do right. now. that defines who I am and what my life is about. So I worked and worked and loved and loved and found my superpowers until I found myself at the top of a small mountain, looking up at the bigger one ahead of me, ready to go see how it feels at the top. My newest favorite thing about myself is my awareness of my own responsibility for the quality of my life. I am 100% in control of how spectacular it is, and I am so excited to make it better than I ever thought it could be. #personaljourney #ohtheplacesyoullgo #drsuess #books #mistakes #empowerment #makeyourlifebeautiful #ginghamphotography

The kind of tired you feel after you've been doing something you LOVE to do with EVERYTHING your soul has to offer the world. I had--CREATED--the opportunity to photograph 15 INCREDIBLE women with extraordinary personalities in extremely vulnerable apparel and watched them transform before my eyes. The vulnerability became a weapon, a tool. I was exhilarated. Because I got to make them feel beautiful, I felt more beautiful.
